 First, we need to determine the total distance Jack traveled and the total time he spent traveling. </think>  
Total distance traveled:  
\begin{align*}
\text{Distance}_1 &= \text{Speed}_1 \times \text{Time}_1 = 40 \text{ mph} \times 1 \text{ hour} = 40 \text{ miles} \\
\text{Distance}_2 &= \text{Speed}_2 \times \text{Time}_2 = 50 \text{ mph} \times 1 \text{ hour} = 50 \text{ miles}
\end{align*}\  
Total distance traveled:  
\begin{align*}
\text{Total Distance} &= \text{Distance}_1 + \text{Distance}_2 = 40 \text{ miles} + 50 \text{ miles} = 90 \text{ miles}
\end{align*}\  
Total time spent traveling:  
\begin{align*}
\text{Total Time} &= \text{Time}_1 + \text{Time}_2 = 1 \text{ hour} + 1 \text{ hour} = 2 \text{ hours}
\end{align*}\  
Average speed:  
\begin{align*}
\text{Average Speed} &= \frac{\text{Total Distance}}{\text{Total Time}} = \frac{90 \text{ miles}}{2 \text{ hours}} = 45 \text{ mph}
\end{align*}\  
The answer is $\boxed{45}$ mph. <answer> 45 </answer>

problem:
In the figure below, a 3-inch by 3-inch square adjoins a 10-inch by 10-inch square. What is the area of the shaded region? Express your answer in square inches as a common fraction. [asy]
unitsize(2mm);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7pt)+fontsize(12pt));

pair H=(0,0), A=(0,10), B=(10,10), C=(10,3), G=(10,0), E=(13,3), F=(13,0);
pair D=extension(A,F,B,G);

draw(A--B--G--H--cycle);
fill(D--C--E--F--cycle, black);
draw(A--F);
draw(G--F--E--C);

label("$A$",A,NW);
label("$H$",H,SW);
label("$B$",B,NE);
label("$C$",C,NE);
label("$G$",G,S);
label("$D$",D,WSW);
label("$E$",E,NE);
label("$F$",F,SE);
[/asy]

